	(9,'../uploads/blog/241373512_23766675_growth.jpg','KLASS BLOG POST','June 25, 2014','<p><strong>Quisque placerat quam ac diam aliquet, nec tristique dolor condimentum. Nullam nunc lorem, euismod id ullamcorper ut, consectetur et nunc. Ut pharetra dui eget odio consequat vulputate. Nunc augue massa, vestibulum quis eleifend sed, hendrerit sed arcu. Pellentesque habitant morbi tristique senectus et netus et malesuada fames ac turpis egestas. Aliquam ac nibh nunc. In sollicitudin nibh vulputate aliquam dapibus. Maecenas ut est ullamcorper, porttitor nunc id, viverra libero. Curabitur tempor neque non ultricies accumsan. Mauris tincidunt dui at ante venenatis congue. Suspendisse in massa vel dui posuere auctor.</strong></p>\n',0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00',0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00',0),
	(10,'blog/84770001_33736448_i1mages.jpg','Blog : Article This is testing long title for long string check is given in the title','jan-26-2010','<p>\n	<img alt=\"\" src=\"http://klass.com/uploads/ckeditor_images/1404475699_Tulips.jpg\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 50px;\" />After a couple months of pain there still looks like some downside for cloud stocks</p>\n<p>\n	It&rsquo;s been a rough couple of months for tech stocks &ndash; more specifically cloud stocks &ndash; and the business press is full of dire warnings. As investors in private technology companies the short-term fluctuations in stock markets are not something we usually pay all that much attention to. However, the sheer volume of ink spilled over it in the past couple of weeks had us wanting to do a bit of digging into the recent tech retreat to see what we could learn. From our review and research we came up with the following insights:<br />\n	Technology in general has been fine &ndash; it is the cloud stocks that got hammered.</p>\n<p>\n	With all the negative attention that the technology space has been getting you would think that the NASDAQ composite would have taken a beating over the past couple of months. It hasn&rsquo;t. It is down less than 1%. Likewise, the S&amp;P 500 Information Technology Sector has been basically flat. The story is in cloud technology. The 35 public cloud technology companies that make up Bessemer Venture Partners&rsquo; Cloud Index were down by an average of 29% from February 28th to April 28th. Cloud leaders like Salesforce and Workday were down 21% and 38% respectively while the old guard like Microsoft (up 7%) and Oracle (up 4%) seemed to benefit from a rebalancing from new to old.</p>\n<p>\n	This followed a period where the Cloud stocks jumped way ahead of the broader NASDAQ and S&amp;P 500. From this it appears to us that this recent fall was a rebalancing within the technology market rather than the beginning of a sector wide shift.<br />\n	Growth is king for cloud companies and EBITDA is largely ignored</p>\n<p>\n	The best possible explanatory value for the recent fall in the value of the companies within the Bessemer Index was revenue growth. As shown below, the higher the 2014 revenue growth the larger the market adjustment over the past couple of months. It seems that the market got ahead of itself on valuing companies by growth and spent the last two months dialing that back.</p>\n<p>\n	Digging further, we found that revenue growth was not only the primary explanatory variable for performance but also for relative value. More interestingly, EBITDA has almost no meaningful explanatory value. In running a series of regressions we found that 2014 expected revenue growth explains roughly 45% of the differing EV to Sales ratios of the Bessemer Index companies. EBITDA margin, which is the primary driver for EV to Sales ratios for more mature companies, was largely uncorrelated with value for high growth cloud company valuations.</p>\n<p>\n	Even with the recent revaluation this relationship does not seem to have changed. The market has dramatically narrowed EV to Sales ratios across the Bessemer Index companies but growth remains the primary value driver with EBITDA contributing very little. Both before and after the fall the market incentive has been for companies to invest profits now for further growth and are happy to defer profitability down the line.<br />\n	[5:46:28 PM] Vimal Patel: htmlspecialchars</p>\n',0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00',0,'2014-07-08 08:02:55',1),
